g.aria-label: This style of graphic is widely used for simple info graphics. Both were vectorized to 8 colors. With no/white background we get after ungrouping easily usable layers.
Simple objects are best redrawn and colored with the pipett tool.
To show some techniques for vectorizing with Inkscape I took the bitmap version (800 px .png file) from 'Bike' by FX13 unchanged and with an added blue background.
Some parts can be gained by 'Path/Break apart' or with the Node tool.
'Cut' parts clean with placing rectangles over unwanted sections and apply 'Path/Difference', always with the main shape and one single rectangle selected. .
Redraw the handles (Line with 3 nodes), convert contour to path and join with bicycle frame.
Some shapes get smaller by vectorizing, resize or mark nodes and adjust with 'Alt+Arrow Keys'.
Gain parts by applying 'Path/Difference' and clean up nodes.

With darker backgrounds we get mostly 'negative' shapes. Put a rectangle below the negative shape, select both, apply 'Path/Difference' and obtain an usable frame (always use a copy of Your objects for all operations - usually both objects get destroyed...)
'Patch' missing parts and 'Path/Join' (always one after another).
Carefully move nodes to get isolated shapes, cut with 'Path/Difference' and remove unneeded nodes.
Inspect the layers gained by vectorization to choose those suitable to create final usable parts by appying 'Path/ Difference'.
Simple objects are best redrawn and colored with the pipett tool.
If You cannot join, check whether it is really an object!
